{{Use Harvard referencing|date=December 2017}} {{italic title}} [[File:Qiyin lüe table 01.png|thumb|right|upright=1.5|First table of the ''Qiyin lüe'']] The '''''Qiyin lüe''''' ({{zh|c=七音略|p=Qīyīn lüè|w=Chi-yin lüeh|l=Seven Sounds Summary}}) is a [[Chinese language|Chinese]] [[rime table]], which dates to before 1161. This reference work survived to the present largely because the [[Song dynasty]] historian Zheng Qiao ({{lang|zh-Hant|鄭樵}}/{{lang|zh-Hans|郑樵 }}; ''Cheng Ch'iao''; 1104–1162) included it in his 1161 encyclopedia ''[[Tongzhi (book)|Tongzhi]]''.
The Chinese linguist [[Luo Changpei]] wrote a definitive study (1935) of the ''Qiyin lüe''.<ref>{{cite journal | surname = Luo | given = Changpei | author-link = Luo Changpei | title = Tōngzhì Qīyīn lüè yánjiū | script-title = 通志七音略研究 | trans-title = Research on the ''Tongzhi Qiyun lue'' | journal = Bulletin of the Institute of History and Philology, Academia Sinica | volume = 5 | year = 1935 | pages = 521–536 }}</ref> The structure and contents of the work is closely related to the ''[[Yunjing]]'', and the two are believed to derive from a common source prior to the Song dynasty.<ref>{{cite book | given = William H. | surname = Baxter | author-link = William H. Baxter | title = A Handbook of Old Chinese Phonology | series = Trends in Linguistics: Studies and Monographs | volume = 64 | location = Berlin and New York | publisher = Mouton de Gruyter | year = 1992 | isbn = 978-3-11-012324-1 | pages = 41–42 }}</ref> Both have tables combining rows for a particular final rime, columns for various initials, and up to four [[Tone (linguistics)|tones]].
